All corporate legal threats, victim testimonies, and institutional documentation have been preserved in our public repository for transparency and accountability. The escalated legal response provides perfect evidence of the retaliation culture that enables sexual violence against foreign women in Korean universities.

This case demonstrates how strategic international pressure can expose systematic sexual violence and corporate intimidation infrastructure. We call on feminist organizations to document this case as evidence of corporate retaliation against accountability advocacy and coordinate solidarity statements supporting victim safety. Film industry networks should assess reputation risks of Korean film industry partnerships and implement accountability standards for international collaborations. Academic institutions must review partnership agreements with Korean universities and implement Title IX compliance assessments for international programs. Government agencies should investigate systematic targeting of foreign women students and implement diplomatic pressure for transparent accountability. Media organizations should cover this story as a case study in corporate intimidation tactics and international accountability advocacy effectiveness.

This campaign demonstrates that viral social media advocacy can create measurable economic pressure on institutions enabling sexual violence, international accountability networks can expose corporate intimidation infrastructure, professional legal threats validate rather than silence accountability advocacy, and corporate panic responses provide evidence of systematic criminal behavior.

The international response will determine whether corporate intimidation succeeds in perpetuating systematic sexual violence against foreign women, transparent investigation establishes justice for victims and protection for future students, international oversight prevents similar exploitation of vulnerable students, and accountability advocacy creates sustainable protection mechanisms.

Female students currently at Dongguk University experiencing harassment or threats should immediately contact their embassy and preserve all evidence of institutional retaliation. Every day of delay potentially exposes additional vulnerable women to systematic sexual violence through this corporate-university partnership arrangement. The international community's immediate response will determine whether corporate intimidation succeeds in silencing victims or whether transparent investigation establishes justice and protection for female students.

